Date:  0/0/1834
Source:  New Zealand (various authors/titles)
Author:  MARKHAM
Vol / Page:  34
Edition:  1963
Quote:  A creeper [torotoro] is used for binding up fences, as we would use Rope Yarns. It is soaked first, or used quite fresh, for what is called (a tie up) [taiapa] a fence to keep Goats out of a Garden or to answer as a railing.
Notes:

Date:  0/0/1838
Source:  New Zealand  (Polack)
Author:  POLACK
Vol / Page:  1/161
Edition:
Quote:  During this melee [e1,e2-acute] they flourished their paddles and hanis, some making use of taiapa [a2,a3-acute], or rail-fence, in lieu of spears : they each returned to their places.<i>Ibid.</i> 1/223 A taiapa [a2-acute], or fence, surrounded each plot of ground to prevent the dogs and pigs from following the natural bent of their inclinations.
Notes:

Date:  0/0/1846
Source:  Journal
Author:  WEEKES
Vol / Page:
Edition:
Quote:  A spot was selected in front of the house and with native assistance a `Tieupha' [i-acute][Taiepa] fence was soon completed. This is made of stout sticks six feet high stuck in the ground perpendicularly and tied round in two or three places with rods and a tough creeper (clematis) more durable than any cord.
Notes:  1846 Weekes's Journal in 1940 Rutherford and Skinner New Plymouth Settlement 120



